Final Project: Using Adversarial Auto Encoders(AAE) to determine the cultural influence of ancient civilizations¶

Authors: Jes ́us Alejandro de Leon Moreno, Yasm ́ın Alejandra Femerling Garc ́ıa, Ishna Satyarth¶

1. Overview:¶

Images of sculptures from Achaemenid, Classi-cal Greek and Hellenistic, Hellenistic Babylonyan, and Neo-Babylonian cultures from the Department of Art History of SMU,Dallas were encoded using an Adversarial Auto-Encoder into a latent 2D space to determine if Hellenistic Babylonyan art has cultural influence from Classical Greek, Neo-Babylonian, or Achaemenid art. Although the results are difficult to interpret,they can be used to help with the subjective resolution of artband historic research in the matter and to set ground to futurework

1.1 AAE Description:¶

In adversarial autoencoder, a GAN performs variational inference by matching the hidden code vector of the autoencoder with a prior distribution. This can be used to map the input images into a model that follows a specified distribution, yielding a latent space that can be visualized in a 2D graph. The autoencoder is trained with a dual objective, one is the reconstruction as a traditional autoencoder, and the other is the adverserial training that matches the distribution of the latent representation of the autoencoder to an arbitrary prior distribution. The encoder learns to convert the data distribution to the prior distribution, and the decoder learns a deep generative model that maps the prior distribution to the data distribution. The adverserial autoencoders are useful in applications such as semi-supervised classification, disentangling style and content of images, unsupervised clustering, dimensionality reductionand data visualization.

We have created the Encoder, Decoder, Discriminator and AutoEncoder classes

In [3]:
#Building model

#Build Encoder
#Used linear model with 3 dense layers and Relu activation function
class Encoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super(Encoder, self).__init__()
        self.dense1= nn.Linear(input_dim, nl1)
        self.dense2 = nn.Linear(nl1, nl2)
        self.dense3 = nn.Linear(nl2, z_dim)
        

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(self.dense1(x))
        x = F.relu(self.dense2(x))
        x = self.dense3(x)
        return x

#Build Decoder
#Used linear model with 3 dense layers and Relu and Sigmoid activation function    
class Decoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super(Decoder, self).__init__()
        self.dense1= nn.Linear(z_dim, nl2)
        self.dense2 = nn.Linear(nl2, nl1)
        self.dense3 = nn.Linear(nl1, input_dim)
        

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(self.dense1(x))
        x = F.relu(self.dense2(x))
        x = F.sigmoid(self.dense3(x))
        return x

#Build Discriminator
#Used linear model with 3 dense layers and Relu and Sigmoid activation function    
class Discriminator(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super(Discriminator, self).__init__()
        self.dense1= nn.Linear(z_dim, nl1)
        self.dense2 = nn.Linear(nl1, nl2)
        self.dense3 = nn.Linear(nl2, 1)
        

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(self.dense1(x))
        x = F.relu(self.dense2(x))
        x = F.sigmoid(self.dense3(x))
        return x 

#Build AutoEncoder
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, coder, decoder):
        super(AutoEncoder, self).__init__()
        self.coder = coder
        self.decoder = decoder
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.coder(x)
        x = self.decoder(x)
        return x

# Plotting the Images in a Latent Space form
def generate_image_grid(step):

    X = imgs
    Y = y_imgs
    
    x_test = torch.reshape(X, [-1,input_dim])
    # Latent space of test set
    x_test_encoded = encoder(x_test).detach().numpy()
    label_list = Y
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    classes = dataset.classes
    colormap = plt.cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(classes)))
    kwargs = {'alpha': 0.8, 'c': [colormap[i] for i in label_list]}
    handles = [mpatches.Circle((0, 0), label=class_, color=colormap[i])
               for i, class_ in enumerate(classes)]
    plt.legend(handles=handles, shadow=True, fancybox=True, loc='center left')
    plt.scatter(x_test_encoded[:, 0], x_test_encoded[:, 1], s=25, **kwargs)
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()
    fig.suptitle('Epoch {} Latent Space'.format(step+1), fontsize=16)
    fig.savefig('res_imgs/Result_from_step_{}.png'.format(step+1))

# Plotting the Final Output
def generate_image_grid_final(name):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    first_batch = []
    for step_graph, (X, Y) in enumerate(dataloader):
        x_test = torch.reshape(X, [-1,input_dim])
        # Latent space of test set
        x_test_encoded = encoder(x_test).detach().numpy()
        label_list = Y
        classes = dataset.classes
        colormap = plt.cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(classes)))
        kwargs = {'alpha': 0.8, 'c': [colormap[i] for i in label_list]}
        handles = [mpatches.Circle((0, 0), label=class_, color=colormap[i])
                   for i, class_ in enumerate(classes)]
        plt.legend(handles=handles, shadow=True, fancybox=True, loc='center left')
        plt.scatter(x_test_encoded[:, 0], x_test_encoded[:, 1], s=25, **kwargs)
        holder = np.where(np.logical_and(x_test_encoded[:, 0] < -2000, x_test_encoded[:, 0] > -10000))
        first_batch.append(X[holder,:,:,:])
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()
    fig.suptitle('Final Epoch Latent Space', fontsize=16)
    fig.savefig('res_imgs/Result_from_final_{}.png'.format(name))
    return first_batch

def get_range(upper, lower):
    first_batch = []
    for step_graph, (X, Y) in enumerate(dataloader):
        x_test = torch.reshape(X, [-1,input_dim])
        # Latent space of test set
        x_test_encoded = encoder(x_test).detach().numpy()
        holder = np.where(np.logical_and(x_test_encoded[:, 0] < upper, x_test_encoded[:, 0] > lower))
        first_batch.append(X[holder,:,:,:])
    return first_batch

%%time
iterations = EPOCHS
total_steps = 0
# TODO: optionally load the checkpoint data here from previous run

# Start training loop
for step in range(iterations):
    total_steps = total_steps+1

    for i, (imgs, y_imgs) in enumerate(dataloader):
        
        autoencoder_optimizer.zero_grad()
        encoder_optimizer.zero_grad()
        discriminator_optimizer.zero_grad()

        x_input = torch.reshape(imgs, [-1,input_dim])
        
        encoder_output = encoder(x_input)
        decoder_output = decoder(encoder_output)
        
        # Autoencoder loss
        autoencoder_loss = torch.mean(torch.pow(x_input.detach() - decoder_output, 2))
        #Update Autoencoder
        autoencoder_loss.backward(retain_graph=True)
        
        real_distribution = torch.from_numpy(np.random.randn(batch_size, z_dim) * 5).float()
        d_fake = discriminator(encoder_output)
        d_real = discriminator(real_distribution)
        
        # Discrimminator Loss
        dc_loss_real = torch.mean(loss_fct(d_real, torch.ones_like(d_real)))
        dc_loss_fake = torch.mean(loss_fct(d_fake, torch.zeros_like(d_fake)))
        dc_loss = dc_loss_fake + dc_loss_real
        #Update Discriminator
        dc_loss.backward(retain_graph=True)
        
        
        
        # Generator loss
        generator_loss = torch.mean(loss_fct(d_fake, torch.ones_like(d_fake)))
        generator_loss.backward()
        
        autoencoder_optimizer.step()
        discriminator_optimizer.step()
        encoder_optimizer.step()
    
    print('EPOCH{:4d}/{:4d}: AE_LOSS: {:.4f} DC_LOSS: {:.4f} GEN_LOSS: {:.4f}'.format(total_steps, iterations, autoencoder_loss.item(), dc_loss.item(), generator_loss.item()))
    
    if step % 20 == 0:
        generate_image_grid(step)
